The idea for the SIRIUS integration is the following:
We want to overload the 2 main functions of the SCF cycle with SIRIUS calls.
These functions are: 
- energy_hamiltonian, which calculates the energy and updates the Hamiltonian
  bassed on an input density/wave functions
- next_density, which soles the eigenvalues problem and spits the new wave
  functions, density, eigenvalues, etc.

This should allow the user to run the SCF in the exact same way as DFTK in
general, with the same mixing schemes and callback functions.

Conceptually, all the numerical details are contained in the basis, and not
the model. Therefore, we do not touch the model itsel, but we create a custom
SiriusBasis. Note for the future: we probably want to keep a normal
PlaneWaveBasis in our  SiriusBasis so that FFTs and other similar operations
can take place on the DFTK side (e.g. for mixing). In the future, we might
also divert those calls to SIRIUS.

In DFTK, the density is simply an array on the real-space grid. We need to
find a way to transfer that data to SIRIUS, such that it can be understood
there too. Then, similar considerations have to be taken such that the
transfer of wave function coefficients can be done as well.

Notes on the energy_hamiltonian function overloading:
- needs to return an Energies and a Hamiltonian struct. Energies is a simple dictionary with the different contributions as keys, and the energies as values. This should be easy to keep in the same format as the current one. The Hamiltonian is gonna be quite different, therefore we need to define a SiriusHamiltonian struct. The SiriusHamiltonian should create a Hamiltonian on the SIRIUS side, and provide a pointer handler to DFTK.

